I noticed in the table that the data type for pounds, metric tons, and dollars is listed as chr. That means these arent seen by R as numbers, but as characters (i.e.text). Its even more annoying because there are commas in the text. This can happen depending on the way the data you load in happens to be formatted.

It makes life difficult for doing data analysis, but we can fix it like this:

herring$Metric.Tons <- as.numeric(gsub(",","",herring$Metric.Tons))
herring$Pounds <- as.numeric(gsub(",","",herring$Pounds))
herring$Dollars <- as.numeric(gsub(",","",herring$Dollars))

Now we can start to get an understanding of relationships within these datasets to help us understand if theres any potential for prediction or forecasting.

Were going to try to use the NAO (which is measured from climate data) to predict the herring catches in Maine. Lets see if the January NAO variable has any relationship to the herring catches.

We want to plot one against the other, but right now, the NAO data goes from the 1800s to 2022, and the herring data goes from 1950 to 2021. Lets line them up.

alldata <- merge(nao,herring,by="Year")

Now we can make some simple plots of any column against any other column.

plot(alldata$Jan.nao,alldata$Metric.Tons)

I dont see a strong relationship there, but maybe if we use all of the data in the NAO table, we might be able to make a prediction. This is where well get into modeling using the TidyModels package.

Build and fit a model

Were using a workflow from tidymodels, which has more examples at this site: https://www.tidymodels.org/start/models/. First we want to divide the data into some that well use to train the model, and some that well use to test how well the model did. Here well use 80% of the data for training and 20% for testing.

data_split <- initial_split(alldata, prop = 8/10)
data_test <- testing(data_split)
data_train <- training(data_split)

The next step is to build a recipe for the model. The first part tells it what to predict, based on which variables. Here, were predicting Metric.Tons as a function of the Jan, Feb, and Mar NAO values. The second part tells it what to use as the data table to work fromhere the training data. This all sets the stage for our modeling.

herring_recipe <- recipe(Metric.Tons ~ Jan.nao + Feb.nao + Mar.nao, data = data_train)

Now we can choose all kinds of different models to use. Well try linear regression. You have to choose an engine as well. This is just a way of refering to the code that runs in the background, that someone else has written to do whatever kind of modeling youre doing. To see the engines, you can do this:

show_engines("linear_reg")
## # A tibble: 7  2
##   engine mode      
##   <chr>  <chr>     
## 1 lm     regression
## 2 glm    regression
## 3 glmnet regression
## 4 stan   regression
## 5 spark  regression
## 6 keras  regression
## 7 brulee regression

Well choose glm. There are other options you can choose. For example, you could do a classification instead of a regression. Well talk about different model choices in class.

lin_mod <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("glm")
lin_mod
## Linear Regression Model Specification (regression)
## 
## Computational engine: glm

The next step is to combine the recipe and the model into a workflow.

wflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lin_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(herring_recipe)

Heres what that workflow contains

wflow

Finally, well put it all together to fit the data using the model and recipe weve built.

herring_fit <- wflow %>% 
  fit(data = data_train)

To compare the prediction to the actual value, you can plot them against each other. First you combine your fitted data to the testing data table. Then you can do a simple plot.

MTpredictions <- augment(herring_fit, data_test)
plot(MTpredictions$.pred,MTpredictions$Metric.Tons)

Finally, you can look at the skill metrics of how the model did. RMSE is root mean square error, RSQ is the r-squared metric, and MAE is the mean absolute error. In this example, these are poor performance values. You would want RMSE and RAE to be small, and/or r-squared to be close to 1.

fit_metrics <- metrics(MTpredictions, truth = Metric.Tons, estimate=.pred)
fit_metrics

Turning it into a forecast

It looks like the NAO is not a great predictor of herring. But so far weve used a given year NAO value to predict that same years herring catch. If we were really going to forecast, we would need to use the NAO value(s) to predict the following years herring catch. We can do this by shifting all of the herring catch data by a year. Lets build a new data table from the herring data, but shift the years by one.

herring_lag <- herring # Copies the 'herring' table to a new variable
herring_lag$Year <- herring_lag$Year - 1 # Subtracts 1 from the year
lagdata <- merge(nao,herring_lag,by="Year") # Makes a combined data table with all data, only now the herring data is lagged by a year

Now we can walk through the same modeling steps with this new data table. Ill combine them together in one block.

data_split <- initial_split(lagdata, prop = 8/10)
data_test <- testing(data_split)
data_train <- training(data_split)
herring_lag_recipe <- recipe(Metric.Tons ~ Jan.nao + Feb.nao + Mar.nao + NAO, data = data_train)
lin_mod <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("glm")
wflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lin_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(herring_lag_recipe)
herring_lag_fit <- wflow %>% 
  fit(data = data_train)
MTpredictions_lag <- augment(herring_lag_fit, data_test)
plot(MTpredictions_lag$.pred,MTpredictions_lag$Metric.Tons)

fit_metrics_lag <- metrics(MTpredictions_lag, truth = Metric.Tons, estimate=.pred)
fit_metrics_lag
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   .metric .estimator   .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>            <dbl>
## 1 rmse    standard   17796.     
## 2 rsq     standard       0.00617
## 3 mae     standard   14088.

This model is a little better, but still not great. It appears that the NAO only has a small amount of predictive power for forecasting herring catches. What other variables might improve this?
